                            <comment id="473786" author="JIRAUSER19503" created="Fri, 3 Oct 2025 07:09:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=adilger&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;adilger&quot;&gt;adilger&lt;/a&gt; When a user writes normally (e.g., &lt;tt&gt;echo &quot;DATA&quot; &amp;gt;&amp;gt; file&lt;/tt&gt;), the MDS automatically marks mirrors 2&#8211;N stale since only mirror 1 was updated.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;However, if the user explicitly uses &lt;tt&gt;lfs mirror write -N 1 &amp;lt;file&amp;gt;&lt;/tt&gt;, then the other mirrors are not automatically marked stale by default. In this case, would you expect &lt;tt&gt;lfs mirror verify --stale&lt;/tt&gt; to detect the difference and mark mirrors 2&#8211;N stale?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="473741" author="adilger" created="Thu, 2 Oct 2025 21:10:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The MDS should automatically mark mirrors 2-10 stale when mirror 1 is being written...  This is just to handle the case where one mirror was broken behind the scenes (e.g. data corruption of an OST file) so that the mirror can be rewritten from the primary mirror.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="473719" author="JIRAUSER19503" created="Thu, 2 Oct 2025 19:11:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=adilger&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;adilger&quot;&gt;adilger&lt;/a&gt; , I wanted to confirm the expected behavior for the &lt;tt&gt;lfs mirror verify --stale&lt;/tt&gt; change. Based on the ticket description, it seems like the intent is to automatically mark stale mirrors when one differs from the others.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For example, if I have a file with 10 mirrors, and I update the first mirror, would running &lt;tt&gt;lfs mirror verify --stale&lt;/tt&gt; then mark mirrors 2&#8211;10 as stale (since they still contain the older content)?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just wanted to make sure this is the behavior you&#8217;re expecting.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
